===============================================================================
CORE COMPONENTS
===============================================================================

RabbitMQ architecture me mainly ye components hote hain:

1. PRODUCER
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Producer wo application/service hoti hai jo message publish karti hai.

Ye published message Exchange ke paas jaata hai.

Producer message ke saath ek routing key bhi bhejta hai.


2. ROUTING KEY
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Routing key ka use Exchange karta hai ye decide karne ke liye
ki message kis queue/s me route kiya jayega.


3. BINDING
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Exchange aur Queue ke beech ek mapping hoti hai
jisko hum Binding bolte hain.

Basically ye Exchange aur Queue ke beech ek connection/link hota hai.


4. QUEUE
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Queue actual storage hoti hai.

1: Messages temporarily yaha stored rehte hain jabtak ki koi consumer unhe process nahi kar leta.

2: Durable Queue:
Suppose:
QueueBuilder.durable("payment.queue")

Meaning:
RabbitMQ crash -> RabbitMQ restart -> queue survives i.e 'payment.queue' still exists.

Queue Durable ≠ Message Durable

These are different things.

Case 1

Durable Queue

✓ queue durable
✗ message non persistent

Rabbit restart -> Queue survives -> Messages may vanish.

Case 2
✓ queue durable
✓ message persistent

Rabbit restart -> Queue survives -> Messages survive.

Example:

public void publishOrderWithSpecificRoutingKey(String message) {

    stringRabbitTemplate.convertAndSend(
            exchange,
            commonBindingKey,
            message,
            msg -> {
                msg.getMessageProperties()
                   .setDeliveryMode(MessageDeliveryMode.PERSISTENT);
                return msg;
            }
    );
}


This is production setup.

3: Non Durable Queue

Suppose:
QueueBuilder.nonDurable("payment.queue")

Meaning:
RabbitMQ crash -> RabbitMQ restart -> Queue disappears -> 'payment.queue' is gone and so is the message.


4: Auto Delete Queue

Queue automatically delete ho jayegi jab uska last consumer unsubscribe/disconnect ho jaye, provided queue par kam se kam ek consumer pehle attach hua ho.

Initial State:

"payment.queue"

Consumers:
- Consumer1
- Consumer2
- Consumer3

Queue exists.

Consumer1 disconnect
payment.queue

Consumers:
- Consumer2
- Consumer3

Queue still exists.

Consumer2 disconnect
Consumers:
- Consumer3

Queue still exists.

Consumer3 disconnect
Consumers:
NONE

Ab RabbitMQ dekhega:

Consumer Count = 0
autoDelete = true

Result:
payment.queue deleted


In Production Generally: autoDelete = false

This is generally used only for temporary queues.

5. CONSUMER
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Consumer wo application/service hoti hai
jo Queue se messages consume karti hai.


6. EXCHANGE
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Exchange decide karta hai:

message kis queue me jayega

based on:

a) Exchange type
b) Routing key
c) Bindings


RabbitMQ me major Exchange types:

1. Direct Exchange
2. Fanout Exchange
3. Topic Exchange
4. Headers Exchange


===============================================================================
A: DIRECT EXCHANGE
===============================================================================

Suppose producer ne message bheja:

    "Hello World"

along with routing key:

    "push"

And there are 3 queues:

-> Push Queue
   binded to Direct Exchange with binding key = "push"

-> Email Queue
   binded to Direct Exchange with binding key = "email"

-> SMS Queue
   binded to Direct Exchange with binding key = "sms"


Ab Direct Exchange apne saare bindings check karega.

Jis queue/s ki binding key exactly:

    "push"

hogi, message usi queue me route kar diya jayega.

Fir consumer us queue se message consume karega.

Is case me message Push Queue me jayega
because uski binding key "push" hai.

Push Consumer us message:

    "Hello World"

ko consume karega and successful processing ke baad
message Push Queue se remove ho jayega.


Producer
   |
   | routingKey = push
   v
Direct Exchange
   |
   |---------------------------------------------------------
   | binding = push       | binding = email   | binding = sms
   v                      v                    v
Push Queue             Email Queue          SMS Queue
   |                      |                    |
   v                      v                    v
Push Consumer         Email Consumer      SMS Consumer


Yaha Direct Exchange basically ek exact-match router ki tarah kaam karta hai.


===============================================================================
B: FANOUT EXCHANGE
===============================================================================

NOTE:
Fanout Exchange me routing key ka koi role nahi hota.

Producer routing key bhej bhi de,
to bhi Fanout Exchange usko ignore kar deta hai.

Kyuki Fanout ka purpose hota hai:

    Broadcasting


Suppose producer ne message bheja:

    "Hello World"

along with routing key:

    "anything"

And there are 3 queues:

-> Push Queue
   binded to Fanout Exchange

-> Email Queue
   binded to Fanout Exchange

-> SMS Queue
   binded to Fanout Exchange


Is case me Fanout Exchange apne saath binded
sabhi queues ko message ki ek independent copy bhej deta hai.

Fanout Exchange routing key ko completely ignore karta hai,
even if producer ne bheja bhi ho to.

Uske liye sirf ek cheez matter karti hai:

    Kaunsi queues is Exchange se bind hain


Once message respective queues me publish ho jaata hai,
respective consumers usko process karte hain and
successful processing ke baad message queue se remove ho jaata hai.


Is case me:

-> Push Queue
-> Email Queue
-> SMS Queue

teeno ko:

    "Hello World"

message ki ek independent copy milegi.


Producer
   |
   | routingKey = anything
   v
Fanout Exchange
   |
   |---------------------------------------------------------
   |                    |                     |
   v                    v                     v
Push Queue          Email Queue           SMS Queue
   |                     |                    |
   |-----|               |                    |
   |     |               |                    |
   v     v               v                    v
Push1  Push2         Email Consumer      SMS Consumer
Consumer Consumer


IMPORTANT:

Agar multiple consumers same Queue ko listen kar rahe hon,
to ek particular message sirf ek hi consumer ko diya jayega.

Example:

Push Queue
   |
   |----> Push1 Consumer
   |
   |----> Push2 Consumer


To koi bhi particular message:

-> ya to Push1 Consumer ko milega
-> ya Push2 Consumer ko

Dono ko same message nahi milega.

Queue internally consumers ke beech load balancing karti hai.


===============================================================================
C: TOPIC EXCHANGE
===============================================================================

Isme pattern matching hoti hai.

Special characters:

* = exactly one word
# = zero or multiple words


Suppose producer ne message bheja:

    "Hello World"

along with routing key:

    "order.created"

And there are 3 queues:

-> SMS Queue
   binded to Topic Exchange with binding:

       order.*

-> Email Queue
   binded to Topic Exchange with binding:

       order.*

-> Payment Queue
   binded to Topic Exchange with binding:

       payment.success


Producer
   |
   | routingKey = order.created
   v
Topic Exchange
   |
   |---------------------------------------------------------
   | binding = order.*     | binding = order.*  | binding = payment.success
   v                       v                     v
SMS Queue              Email Queue          Payment Queue
   |                       |                     |
   |------|                |                     |
   |      |                |                     |
   v      v                v                     v
SMS1   SMS2           Email Consumer      Payment Consumer
Consumer Consumer


Ab Topic Exchange incoming routing key:

    order.created

ko apni sabhi bindings ke saath pattern matching karega.


routingKey = order.created


Now:

order.*         -> MATCH
order.*         -> MATCH
payment.success -> NO MATCH


Isliye Topic Exchange:

-> SMS Queue ko "Hello World" ki ek copy bhej dega
-> Email Queue ko bhi "Hello World" ki ek independent copy bhej dega
-> Payment Queue ko koi message nahi milega
   because binding match nahi hui


Once messages respective queues me publish ho jaate hain,
un queues ke consumers messages consume karte hain.

Successful processing ke baad consumer ACK bhejta hai,
jiske baad RabbitMQ message ko queue se remove kar deta hai.


IMPORTANT:

Agar multiple consumers same queue ko listen kar rahe hon,
to ek particular message sirf ek hi consumer ko diya jayega.

Example:

SMS Queue
   |
   |----> SMS1 Consumer
   |
   |----> SMS2 Consumer


To:

    "Hello World"

message either:

-> SMS1 Consumer ko milega
-> ya SMS2 Consumer ko

Dono ko nahi.

RabbitMQ same queue ke consumers ke beech
load balancing karta hai using:

    Competing Consumers Pattern


NOTE:

Agar multiple queues same binding ke saath
Exchange se bind hoti hain,
to un sabhi queues ko message ki ek independent copy milti hai.

Is example me:

-> SMS Queue
-> Email Queue

dono ko:

    "Hello World"

message ki ek independent copy milti hai.


