8. MESSAGE ACKNOWLEDGEMENT
===============================================================================

Suppose there is a queue named:

payment-queue

which currently contains three messages:

msg1
msg2
msg3

There is a consumer named:

payment-consumer

which is listening to this queue.

RabbitMQ delivers:

msg1

to the consumer.

Question:

How does RabbitMQ know that the consumer has successfully processed
the message and it can now be safely removed from the queue?

Answer:

ACKNOWLEDGEMENT (ACK)

Flow:

Queue
|
deliver msg1
|
Consumer
|
process message
|
send ACK
|
RabbitMQ removes msg1 permanently

---

## RABBITMQ MESSAGE STATES

A message can be in one of the following states:

1. READY
2. UNACKNOWLEDGED

Example:

Queue:

msg1
msg2
msg3

RabbitMQ delivers msg1 to the consumer.

Now the state becomes:

READY:
msg2
msg3

UNACKNOWLEDGED:
msg1

Until RabbitMQ receives an ACK, the message remains in the
UNACKNOWLEDGED state.

---

## HOW DOES SPRING BOOT HANDLE ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS?

Spring Boot provides three acknowledgement modes:

1. AUTO
2. MANUAL
3. NONE

These are controlled using:

spring.rabbitmq.listener.simple.acknowledge-mode

Example:

spring.rabbitmq.listener.simple.acknowledge-mode=auto

or

spring.rabbitmq.listener.simple.acknowledge-mode=manual

or

spring.rabbitmq.listener.simple.acknowledge-mode=none

===============================================================================
1. AUTO MODE
===============================================================================

This is the default acknowledgement mode.

In AUTO mode, Spring automatically decides whether an ACK or NACK
needs to be sent based on the outcome of listener execution.

---

## CASE 1: LISTENER EXECUTES SUCCESSFULLY

Suppose RabbitMQ delivers:

msg1

Listener processes the message successfully.

Internally, RabbitMQ provides the following API for acknowledging
messages:

channel.basicAck(deliveryTag, multiple);

Spring uses this API internally when listener execution completes
successfully.

## UNDERSTANDING THE PARAMETERS OF basicAck()

1. deliveryTag

A delivery tag is a unique identifier assigned by RabbitMQ to every
message delivered to a consumer within a channel

RabbitMQ uses this tag to uniquely identify messages while processing
ACKs.

---

2. multiple

---

If:

multiple=false

Only the message represented by the supplied delivery tag will be
ACKed.

Example:

channel.basicAck(103,false);

Only message 103 is ACKed.

---

If:

multiple=true

RabbitMQ will ACK all currently unacknowledged messages up to and
including the supplied delivery tag.

Example:

Suppose:

msg1 -> tag=101
msg2 -> tag=102
msg3 -> tag=103

Then:

channel.basicAck(103, true);

Meaning:

msg1
msg2
msg3

All three messages will be ACKed together.

This is particularly useful in batch-processing scenarios.


Flow:

msg1
|
listener executes successfully
|
Spring sends ACK basicAck(101, false)
|
RabbitMQ removes msg1 permanently

Once RabbitMQ receives this ACK, the message is permanently removed
from the queue.

---

## CASE 2: LISTENER THROWS AN EXCEPTION

Suppose listener execution fails:

msg1
|
listener throws exception
|
Spring sends NACK / REJECT


RabbitMQ provides two APIs for this:

---

## a) REJECT

channel.basicReject( deliveryTag, requeue );

Example:

channel.basicReject(101,true);

Limitation:

basicReject() can reject only a single message.

---

## b) NACK

channel.basicNack(deliveryTag,multiple,requeue);

Example:

channel.basicNack(101,false,true);

Capability:

basicNack() can reject either a single message or multiple messages.

Because of this, NACK is essentially a more powerful version of
REJECT.

---

## UNDERSTANDING THE PARAMETERS OF basicNack()

1. deliveryTag

A delivery tag is a unique identifier assigned by RabbitMQ to every
message delivered to a consumer within a channel.

RabbitMQ uses this tag to uniquely identify messages while processing NACKs.

---

2. multiple

---

If:

multiple=false

Only the message represented by the supplied delivery tag will be
NACKed.

Example:

channel.basicNack(103,false,true);

Only message 103 is NACKed.

---

If:

multiple=true

RabbitMQ will NACK all currently unacknowledged messages up to and
including the supplied delivery tag.

Example:

Suppose:

msg1 -> tag=101
msg2 -> tag=102
msg3 -> tag=103

Then:

channel.basicNack(103,true,true);

Meaning:

msg1
msg2
msg3

All three messages will be NACKed together.

This is particularly useful in batch-processing scenarios.

---

3. requeue

---

The requeue parameter determines whether the rejected message should
be placed back into the queue or not.

Spring decides the value of this parameter using following property:

spring.rabbitmq.listener.simple.default-requeue-rejected

CASE 1:
spring.rabbitmq.listener.simple.default-requeue-rejected = true

Flow:

msg1
|
listener throws exception
|
Spring catches exception
|
Spring sends NACK / REJECT
|
|   channel.basicNack(tag,false,true)
|        OR
|   channel.basicReject(tag,true)
|
RabbitMQ receives NACK/REJECT with requeue = true
|
RabbitMQ puts message back into queue

---

## WHY IS REQUEUEING NOT ALWAYS A GOOD IDEA?

Consider the following malformed message:

{
"amount":"ABC"
}

Consumer code:

Integer.parseInt("ABC");

This will always throw an exception.

If requeue=true:

consume -> fail -> requeue
consume -> fail -> requeue
consume -> fail -> requeue

The same message keeps coming back forever.

This situation is known as a:

POISON MESSAGE

and can result in an infinite processing loop.

Production systems generally try to avoid such scenarios.

CASE 2:
spring.rabbitmq.listener.simple.default-requeue-rejected=false

Flow:

msg1
|
listener throws exception
|
Spring catches exception
|
Spring sends NACK / REJECT
|
|   channel.basicNack(tag,false, false)
|        OR
|   channel.basicReject(tag, false)
|
RabbitMQ receives NACK/REJECT with requeue = false
   |
RabbitMQ
      |
DLX configured ?
      |
      +-- NO --> Drop Message
      |
      +-- YES
              |
              v
      Publish to DLX
              |
              v
      DLQ receives message

Note:
Message is dead-lettered to the configured DLX,
which then routes the message to the appropriate DLQ.

## PRODUCTION RECOMMENDATION

Most production systems use:

spring.rabbitmq.listener.simple.default-requeue-rejected=false

along with a properly configured Dead Letter Queue (DLQ).

This prevents infinite poison-message loops and allows failed messages
to be analyzed, retried, or handled separately without affecting
normal message processing.


## CASE 3: CONSUMER CRASHES BEFORE SENDING ACK/NACK

Suppose:

msg1
|
Queue delivers message
|
Message state becomes:
UNACKNOWLEDGED
|
Consumer starts processing
|
Consumer crashes (or network connection is lost)
|
No ACK / NACK / REJECT  received
|
RabbitMQ detects that the consumer's channel/TCP connection has closed
|
RabbitMQ marks msg1 as READY again
|
RabbitMQ requeues the message
|
Message becomes available for redelivery
|
Same consumer (after restart)
OR
Another consumer can consume it

===============================================================================
1. MANUAL MODE
